							<div class="entry-content">
								
<p class="has-drop-cap">Because car enthusiasts are such a wildly differing bunch of people who all tend to fall into their different automotive tribes, it can be difficult to pick a thoughtful Christmas gift for the car lover in your life.</p>



<p>Like hitting a patch of seasonal black ice, though, when it comes to buying a Christmas present for the discerning car fan, the important thing is not to panic. In fact, there’s absolutely no reason to panic in this instance, because even if you’re flat out of ideas for car-themed gifts, we’ve got you covered. Whether it’s toys, clothes, gadgets, books, video games or stocking fillers, below you’ll find our round-up of the best automotive-inspired gifts for Christmas 2023.</p>



<p>The prices are mostly the recommended retail prices but are subject to change and many will be discounted from the date of publication until Black Friday, so don&#8217;t miss out. Happy shopping! </p>



<ul>
<li><a href="#driving_toys">Toys and games</a></li>



<li><a href="#video_games">Video games and consoles</a></li>



<li><a href="#driving_books">Books, films and art</a></li>



<li><a href="#driving_experiences">Experiences</a></li>



<li><a href="#driving_gadgets">Tech and tools</a></li>



<li><a href="#driving_clothing">Clothing and apparel</a></li>



<li><a href="#driving_cleaning">Car cleaning and accessories</a> </li>



<li><a href="#driving_stockings">Stocking fillers</a></li>
</ul>



<p><em>Want a few high end motoring gift ideas? Click <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/c9984d94-eb74-4f94-99aa-54367f8693f4?shareToken=11c9853e434464408ae651cf88f0b92a" target="_blank">here</a> for a list created by our friends at Times Luxx.</em></p>



<hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity"/>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="driving_toys"><strong>Toys and games</strong></h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>1. <strong>Mercedes-AMG G 63 Licensed Ride-On 12V</strong></strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1151" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?w=1024" alt="Mercedes G Wagon ride-on toy" class="wp-image-136946" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png 1200w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=310,297 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=768,737 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=1024,982 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=402,386 402w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=234,224 234w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=467,448 467w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=260,249 260w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-2.png?resize=519,498 519w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></figure>



<p>If your child wants to motor about your garden like an absolute baller, they could do a lot worse than this fully licensed Mercedes-AMG G 63 ride-on. With various features of the madcap G 63 carried over, such as a quilted appearance for the seat and side-exit exhausts (fake, obvs), this 12-volt, twin-motor electric car has the proper kerbside cachet for your child. </p>



<p>The G 63 ride-on also comes with a 2.4G parental remote control as a safety override if you need it, but with seatbelts, a soft-start function and a top speed of 3mph — plus the legendary strength of the Mercedes G-Class, obviously — your child should be nice and safe in this beauty. </p>



<p>And they can even listen to their favourite tunes as they drive along, thanks to full onboard multimedia connectivity.</p>



<p><strong>Price</strong> £219.95<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.outdoortoys.com/products/licensed-mercedes-benz-g63-12v-children-s-ride-on-jeep?variant=45443230335291" target="_blank">OutdoorToys.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>2. <strong>Lego Icons Chevrolet Corvette 1961</strong></strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="591" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?w=1024" alt="Chevrolet Corvette Lego" class="wp-image-136947" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png 1200w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=310,153 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=768,378 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=1024,504 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=620,305 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=360,177 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=720,355 720w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=400,197 400w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-3.png?resize=800,394 800w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></figure>



<p>Lego’s Creator Expert series — intricate sets aimed at older, more experienced builders — has been doing some wonderful classic car sets for years now, and the latest addition to the canon is this marvellous C1 first-generation Corvette. As a 1961 model, it has the later ducktail rear end with the Corvette’s now-trademark quad rear lights, a look which evolved into one of the most beautiful cars ever built, the C2 Corvette Stingray.</p>



<p>Nevertheless, this Roman Red original is a blocky little beauty and, like many of the recent Creator kits, you’ve got the choice of building it as either an open-top or a fixed-head coupé. It’s a 1,210-piece construction, so Lego says it is suitable for those 18-plus, but a keen parent could build it in tandem with a tweenager as a nice Christmassy thing to bring families together.</p>



<p>This would go perfectly with the Danish company’s Ford Mustang and Chevrolet Corvette Z28 kits, if you know someone who’s got the Lego illness and has already bagged the other two bits of classic Americana… but we couldn’t possibly comment.</p>



<p><strong>Price</strong> £129.99<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.lego.com/en-gb/product/chevrolet-corvette-1961-10321" target="_blank">Lego.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>3. Hot Wheels Criss Cross Crash</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="679" height="393" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-121212" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg 679w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg?resize=310,179 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg?resize=620,359 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg?resize=360,208 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/hot.jpg?resize=400,232 400w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></figure>



<p>A blast from the past for many no doubt, Hot Wheels’ Criss Cross Crash is still going strong, still delivering its hypnotic blend of speed and mayhem. </p>



<p>How it works is simple — users place two or more little cars (the more the merrier) onto the assembled track whereupon they’re propelled around the banking by battery-operated rollers until they crash spectacularly to the delight of all present. </p>



<p>Be sure, if ordering, to order a couple of Hot Wheels die-cast cars along with it as there’s only one included in the set, and it’s not a whole lot of fun with just one. Definitely not recommended for use with dad’s set of vintage Matchbox models.</p>



<p><strong>Price</strong> £34.99<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/Hot-Wheels-DTN42-Criss-Cross/dp/B01ARGC5F4#productDetails" target="_blank">Amazon.co.uk</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>4. Lego 1969 Chevrolet Camaro Z/28</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1440" height="897" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?w=1024" alt="1969 Chevy Camaro Z28 by Lego" class="wp-image-116832" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg 1440w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=310,193 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=768,478 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=1024,638 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=620,386 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=360,224 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=720,448 720w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=400,249 400w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/07/lego-003.jpg?resize=800,498 800w" sizes="(max-width: 1440px) 100vw, 1440px" /></figure>



<p>A hot classic car-inspired kit brought out for last Christmas, this is a brick version of the 1969 Chevrolet Camaro Z28. Builders of the Camaro have the choice of assembling it as a hardtop or convertible with the added option of exposed or hidden headlights.</p>



<p>It&#8217;s not as complex as something like the<strong>&nbsp;</strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.lego.com/en-gb/product/lamborghini-sian-fkp-37-42115" target="_blank">Lego Technics Lamborghini Sian</a> but, with 1,458 pieces, the finished model is a substantial beast, measuring just over 36cm in length and 14cm wide. It&#8217;s also beautifully detailed and includes functional elements such as working steering, an engine with moving parts and doors that open and close. It&#8217;s customisable, too, with alternative body panels to get the look you want.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£149.99<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a href="https://go.skimresources.com?id=34784X1557322&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.lego.com%2Fen-gb%2Fproduct%2Fchevrolet-camaro-z28-10304" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Lego.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>5. Baghera Racing Car</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="800" height="800" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png" alt="Baghera racing car toy" class="wp-image-136948" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png 800w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=310,310 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=768,768 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=620,620 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=360,360 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=386,386 386w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=224,224 224w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=448,448 448w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=249,249 249w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-4.png?resize=498,498 498w" sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px" /></figure>



<p>Sometimes, abstract style is better than 100 per cent modelling accuracy and this beautiful retro racer from Baghera is a great example of that. Its simple but attractive lines evoke streamlined motorsport cars of the 1950s and ‘60s, and the tough body is made of ABS plastic that is lacquered and hand-polished to a pristine finish. Add in big, chunky wheels with proper rubber tyres on them and it’s a thing of genuine ergonomic beauty.</p>



<p>Available in four colours — red, blue, green and crisp silver — and measuring a sizeable 18cm long, the cars also have different numbers on them, so you can either collect the set over time or just buy all of them to put them on display somewhere; yes, they’d be just as good for eye-catching interior décor as they would be racing around the living room floor in the hands of a young child.</p>



<p><strong>Price</strong> £33.95<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://thelovelylittletoyshop.co.uk/product/racing-car-silver/" target="_blank">The Lovely Little Toy Shop</a> (N.b. this is a shop founded by the wife of one of our writers)</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>6. <strong>Bentley Bears</strong></strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1896" height="1896" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png" alt="Bentley cars teddy bear" class="wp-image-137010" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png 1896w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=310,310 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=768,768 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=1024,1024 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=1536,1536 1536w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=620,620 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=360,360 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=386,386 386w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=224,224 224w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=448,448 448w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=249,249 249w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-5-edited.png?resize=498,498 498w" sizes="(max-width: 1896px) 100vw, 1896px" /></figure>



<p>They really should have called one of these “Woolf Bearnato”, in homage to one of the famous Bentley Boys of the 1920s. Still, if you’re looking for a car-related gift with a difference, these top-end teddy bears from British luxury marque Bentley ought to suffice. </p>



<p>There are four to choose from, with three costing £65 each. These are the Engineer teddy bear, the Heritage Racing teddy bear and the Cosy Knit teddy bear. The former two relate to Bentley’s motorsport exploits, with the Engineer resplendent in white and green overalls with a matching cap, while the Heritage Racing bear is an epitome of 1930s gentleman racers — leather bomber jacket, racing goggles and a suedette helmet. Plus a polka-dot scarf of the kind that was worn by Sir Henry “Tim” Birkin, father of the famous supercharged Bentley Blower. James Bond used to drive one of those in the Ian Fleming books, you know.</p>



<p>The Cosy Knit teddy is said to be the “baby” of the Bentley bear family, hence it is wearing a coordinated knitted jumper and bobble hat for maximum cuteness. </p>



<p>That just leaves the Special Edition Signature Bear, which has flexible joints and a double-ribbon necktie in grey and green. This one is pricier than the others at £80, but all four bears have a Bentley ‘B’ embroidered on one paw and measure 40cm tall. Each one is presented in a 100 per cent cotton Bentley-branded dust bag to keep them clean when they’re not being carted lovingly around the house by their proud new owner.</p>



<p><strong>Price</strong> £65-80<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://shop.bentleymotors.com/products/heritage-bear" target="_blank">BentleyMotors.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>7. Ferrari Testa Rossa J ride-on car</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1500" height="814" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?w=1024" alt="The Little Car Company Ferrari Testa Rossa J" class="wp-image-121213" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png 1500w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=310,168 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=768,417 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=1024,556 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=620,336 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=360,195 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=720,391 720w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=400,217 400w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/image.png?resize=800,434 800w" sizes="(max-width: 1500px) 100vw, 1500px" /></figure>



<p>The Bicester-based Little Car Company specialises in producing scaled-down versions of famous classics such as the Bugatti Type 35 and Aston Martin DB5, all built to unbelievably high standards.</p>



<p>One of the firm’s latest creations is a 75%-scale version of the 1957 Ferrari 250 Testa Rossa, one of the best-known racing cars of the fifties and sixties. The car has been officially sanctioned by Maranello, its design being based on original drawings obtained from Ferrari’s archive, and there’s the option of customising each example in a period-correct livery with the assistance of Ferrari Classiche.</p>



<p>Rather than a pint-sized rendering of the fabled Colombo V12, the Testa Rossa J (the J stands for “Junior”), is powered by a 16bhp electric motor giving the Little Car Company’s Ferrari a top speed of 50mph with several selectable driving modes controlling the power delivery to ensure that it’s safe whatever the driving abilities of the person behind the wheel. Because of its performance, it’s recommended for ages 14 and above — and even accommodates an adult measuring 6ft 5in, we can confirm. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large is-style-default"><img decoding="async" width="7128" height="4752" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-121446" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg 7128w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=310,207 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=768,512 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=1024,683 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=1536,1024 1536w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=2048,1365 2048w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=579,386 579w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=336,224 336w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=672,448 672w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=374,249 374w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2022/11/DSC04211.jpg?resize=747,498 747w" sizes="(max-width: 7128px) 100vw, 7128px" /></figure>



<p>Given that the Testa Rossa gets genuine Ferrari chassis plates, it could also be argued that it’s actually Ferrari’s first fully-electric vehicle, and one with a range of around 62 miles at that, though it&#8217;s not one built in Maranello — these are very British interpretations.</p>



<p>While the level of workmanship is staggering, so is the price: each of the 299 Testa Rossa Js start from around £82,000, which is a positively eye-watering price for a vehicle that isn’t road-legal. Regardless, with so few examples slated for production, your chances of getting your hands on one are vanishingly slim.</p>



<p><strong>Price </strong>c.£82,000+<br><strong>Buy it at </strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.testarossaj.com/" target="_blank">The Little Car Company</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>8. Porsche 911 Dakar with Christmas tree 1:43</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1920" height="1081" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png" alt="" class="wp-image-137011" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png 1920w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=310,175 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=768,432 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=1024,577 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=1536,865 1536w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=620,349 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=360,203 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=720,405 720w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=400,225 400w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-6-edited.png?resize=800,450 800w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px" /></figure>



<p>The <a href="https://www.driving.co.uk/car-reviews/video-review/porsche-911-dakar-video-review-getting-to-grips-with-off-road-911-on-snow/" data-type="post" data-id="124198" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Porsche Dakar</a> is a 911 with a difference — a rough-rider standing tall on its suspension and wistfully reminiscing about the German manufacturer’s success in the 1980s on the most gruelling motorsport event of them all, the Paris-Dakar rally (now just the Dakar).</p>



<p>And so while there are plenty of splendid models of Porsche’s highly desirable road-car range available in the Porsche catalogue, it’s this little 1:43 scale version of the Dakar with a Christmas tree strapped to its roof that caught our eye. Because the incongruous sight of a Norwegian spruce lashed to the top of one of the most famous sports cars in the world is one worth celebrating in miniature.</p>



<p><strong>Price </strong>£70<br><strong>Buy it at </strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://shop.porsche.com/gb/en-GB/p/porsche-911-dakar-992-with-christmas-tree-christmas-limited-P-WAP0200020RXMS/WAP0200020RXMS" target="_blank">Porsche.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>9. <strong>Hot Wheels City Speedway Hauler</strong></strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="600" height="600" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png" alt="" class="wp-image-136951" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png 600w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=310,310 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=360,360 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=386,386 386w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=224,224 224w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=448,448 448w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=249,249 249w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-7.png?resize=498,498 498w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></figure>



<p>A gift that performs the dual purpose of keeping your house tidy, <em>and </em>it’ll entertain the kids for hours? Sounds too good to be true, right? Not with this brilliant Hot Wheels City Speedway Hauler. </p>



<p>In its most compact form, it looks like a car transporter and will house up to 22 Hot Wheels models — great for keeping them from going under mum and dad’s feet, for instance. Yet the whole thing folds out into a six-foot-long, two-lane drag strip, with the cab featuring a launch mechanism for simple yet highly effective head-to-head racing. </p>



<p>A small blue gate at the end of the track also flips after the “winning” car has gone through, causing the losing vehicle to crash off the track — trust us, your kids are going to love that feature. And, like any Hot Wheels track-based merch, it’ll connect to other playsets for maximum versatility.</p>



