<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="driving_gadgets"><strong>Tech and tools</strong></h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>1. Nextbase iQ smart dash cam</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1194" height="897" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg" alt="Nextbase iQ dash cam" class="wp-image-137050" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg 1194w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=310,233 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=768,577 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=1024,769 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=514,386 514w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=298,224 298w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=596,448 596w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=331,249 331w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Nextbase-iQ-dash-cam-edited.jpg?resize=663,498 663w" sizes="(max-width: 1194px) 100vw, 1194px" /></figure>



<p>If you&#8217;ve been jealous of Tesla drivers with their 360-degree cameras and &#8220;Sentry mode&#8221;, then this could be your solution. It does all the usual dash cam stuff, yes, and the top spec model records the road ahead in crystal clear 4K resolution. But it also has a camera pointing into the cabin, offering a 180-degree view that captures the view through the side windows. Combine that with radar sensors and you get a very smart security device that will capture thieves before they break into your car, and record clips to the cloud. </p>



<p>It also has a Witness Mode, which is voice activated and records 30 mins of video in case unwanted people approach your car while stopped at traffic lights&#8230; or in case you want a record when pulled over by the police. </p>



<p>Other smart features include sensors that can detect the speed of other vehicles, and even create an animation of an accident to send to insurers. See our <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.driving.co.uk/news/products/nextbase-iq-review-first-test-of-the-worlds-smartest-dash-cam/" data-type="post" data-id="136249" target="_blank">full review of the new Nextbase iQ here</a>.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£349-449, depending on version. For smart features, a monthly subscription of £6.99 or £9.99 is required.<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a href="https://fave.co/46ddhue" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Halfords.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>2. All-new Echo Auto (2nd generation)&nbsp;</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1000" height="967" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-137053" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg 1000w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=310,300 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=768,743 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=399,386 399w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=232,224 232w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=463,448 463w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=257,249 257w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/61xBAkVkfpL._AC_SL1000_.jpg?resize=515,498 515w" sizes="(max-width: 1000px) 100vw, 1000px" /></figure>



<p>While the quality of virtual assistants in cars is rapidly improving, the systems in used cars can often be more hindrance than help, meaning you may have to divert your attention away from the road and onto fiddly physical controls. Bringing in the help of an established assistant like Amazon’s Alexa can make driving a more serene and more safe experience, and brings many of your phone apps into the fold to transform your journeys</p>



<p>The updated Echo Auto allows hands free operation of music apps such as Amazon Music, Apple Music and Spotify, as well as podcast and audiobook apps. It also has the ability to set navigation destinations and control smart home devices from the car with your voice.</p>



<p>Do note, though, that it&#8217;s not compatible with all cars: check whether it&#8217;ll work with your <a href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/gp/browse.html?node=82890630031&amp;ref=uk_wwytk_grw_aucc" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">here</a>.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£59.99<br><strong>Buy it at</strong> <a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://www.amazon.co.uk/echo-auto-2nd-gen/dp/B09Y13TCNZ/ref=asc_df_B09Y13TCNZ/" target="_blank">Amazon.co.uk</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>3. Garmin Mini 2 dash cam</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1364" height="768" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png" alt="Garmin mini dash cam" class="wp-image-137077" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png 1364w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=310,175 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=768,432 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=1024,577 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=620,349 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=360,203 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=720,405 720w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=400,225 400w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-19-edited.png?resize=800,450 800w" sizes="(max-width: 1364px) 100vw, 1364px" /></figure>



<p>If you want a good dash cam but on a budget, then try the Garmin Mini 2. Despite its diminutive size — it’s described as being as big as a car key, allowing for discreet mounting near your interior mirror — it can still film in 1080p HD video and is fitted with a 140-degree wide-angle lens. It will also automatically upload saved incident footage to the Garmin cloud “Video Vault”, so that you know you’ve got those all-important clips saved in perpetuity for future reference.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£99.99<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a href="https://fave.co/40DdaH6" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Argos.co.uk</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>4. Porsche Speaker 2.0 / ‘60 Years Of 911’ Version</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="1343" height="1344" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-137079" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg 1343w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=310,310 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=768,769 768w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=1024,1024 1024w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=620,620 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=360,360 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=386,386 386w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=224,224 224w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=448,448 448w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=249,249 249w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Porsche-speaker-edited.jpeg?resize=498,498 498w" sizes="(max-width: 1343px) 100vw, 1343px" /></figure>



<p>A high-end Bluetooth speaker, this little beauty is designed to look like one of the tailpipes on the exhaust system of a Porsche 911 — perfect for a car fan who’s also a home audiophile. </p>



<p>There are two versions, the regular model for £461, or a limited-build run to celebrate 60 years of the 911 itself, which is one of 1,963 units (that, of course, being the year the 911 arrived); this one is an extra £40 and has an inscription on it denoting its restricted availability. </p>



<p>Either version features Qualcomm aptX hi-def wireless audio, measures 215mm long, weighs 1.1kg and comes with an attractive carry case.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£461 or £501<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://shop.porsche.com/gb/en-GB/p/911-speaker-20-porsche-originals-P-WAP0501100PSPK/WAP0501100PSPK?queryID=af5b8b822c4eda1690b5e338ad44111f" target="_blank">Porsche.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>5. Ghost II immobiliser</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img decoding="async" width="636" height="394" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png?w=636" alt="Ghost II vehicle immobiliser" class="wp-image-137033" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png 636w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png?resize=310,192 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png?resize=620,384 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png?resize=360,224 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/image-21.png?resize=400,249 400w" sizes="(max-width: 636px) 100vw, 636px" /></figure>



<p>This is a beauty of a security device. It needs professionally wiring into your car but the Ghost II immobiliser works by creating your a PIN from your vehicle’s own interior buttons on the dashboard and steering wheel. So, until you press a certain sequence of buttons of your choosing, the car won’t start at all, even with the key present, preventing “relay thefts” or anyone who has your car key without your permission from driving the car no matter what they do. </p>



<p>Diagnostic tools typically used by car thieves cannot detect the Ghost, hence its name, and it comes with both a two-year warranty and also a smartphone app for easy operation.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£99.99<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a href="https://ghostinstallations.co.uk/product/ghost-immobiliser/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">GhostInstallations.co.uk</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>6. Tile Mate</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="707" height="400" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-137080" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg 707w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg?resize=310,175 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg?resize=620,351 620w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg?resize=360,204 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/Tile-mate.jpg?resize=400,226 400w" sizes="(max-width: 707px) 100vw, 707px" /></figure>



<p>A returning favourite from last year and such a straightforward little gift idea. For anyone who’s a bit forgetful when leaving their car keys around the place, simply attach a Tile Mate to the bunch and then the owner can use a smartphone app to get the Mate to emit a high-pitched beep — making the “lost” keys easy and quick to locate. </p>



<p>It’s got a working range of up to 76 metres and is powered by a battery that should last for up to three years. It’s also compatible with both Android and Apple devices.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£19.99<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a href="https://fave.co/3SGNUhp" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Tile.com</a></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>7. CTEK MXS 5.0 T battery charger</strong></h3>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="555" height="555" src="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-137081" srcset="https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg 555w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=310,310 310w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=360,360 360w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=386,386 386w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=224,224 224w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=448,448 448w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=249,249 249w, https://www.driving.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2023/11/CTEK-MXS-battery-charger.jpg?resize=498,498 498w" sizes="(max-width: 555px) 100vw, 555px" /></figure>



<p>This is not a glamorous gift but, for anyone who owns an older car or motorbike which they only use on high days and holidays, the CTEK battery charger is an absolute godsend. </p>



<p>It plugs into a three-pin domestic socket at one end and then, through the crocodile clips typical of external car-battery charging systems, attaches to a car’s battery at the other. It’ll then either “condition” the battery by pulsing electricity into it periodically to keep the charge level topped up, or it will even recover a deeply discharged 12-volt battery. And it should work with any type of vehicle battery, including ones designed for cars with engine stop/start systems.</p>



<p>It can work in extremes of temperature and has a clear, simple design with an eight-light display to show the current state of the battery/charging cycle. </p>



<p>Attach one of these beauties to a garage queen car and it is guaranteed to start up smoothly the next time it is needed, even if it stands immobile for months at a time.</p>



<p><strong>Price&nbsp;</strong>£81.99<br><strong>Buy it at&nbsp;</strong><a rel="noreferrer noopener" href="https://fave.co/3QHKGri" target="_blank">Halfords.com</a></p>



